</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[264,1324,284,1870]" box="[312,1064,1684,1710]" pageId="12" pageNumber="35">Etymology. This new species is named for the island of Basilan.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[264,1324,284,1870]" lastBlockId="13.[264,1323,284,350]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="12" pageNumber="35">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName box="[434,782,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachycoraebus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basilanensis">
<emphasis box="[434,782,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="35">Brachycoraebus basilanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to 
<taxonomicName box="[929,1142,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachycoraebus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mindanaoensis">
<emphasis box="[929,1142,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="35">B. mindanaoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and differs by being smaller, with more blue­green to green tints distributed on the dorsal surface, a difference in the color and sculpture of the hypomeron, the pronotal proportions, the wider emargination of the last visible abdominal ventrite and the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1086,1231,1844,1870]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="13.[264,383,1427,1451]" captionTargetBox="[489,1092,432,1404]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[374,1365,422,1419]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14, Brachycoraebus spp.; Fig. 9, B. luzonicus Obenberger, holotype; Figs. 10, 13, B. mindanaoensis, sp. nov., Fig. 10, dorsal habitus; Fig. 13, aedeagus; Figs. 11, 14, B. basilanensis, sp. nov., Fig. 11, dorsal habitus; Fig. 14, aedeagus; Fig. 12, B. minutus, sp. nov., dorsal habitus; scale bars for Figs. 10 – 12 = 1.0 mm, Figs. 12 – 14 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/169784/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="35">Figs. 13, 14</figureCitation>
). These species are relatively close geographically since Basilan lies due south of the southwestern apex of the Zamboanga Peninsula of Mindanao.
</paragraph>
